The paper deals with lower bounds on the complexity of Boolean functions, which is a central topic in computational complexity theory. Specifically, it focuses on the threshold degree and sign-rank of $\text{AC}^{0}$ circuits, which are important models of computation in complexity theory. This makes cs.CC (Computational Complexity) the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves techniques from linear algebra, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) as likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the discrepancy, threshold weight, and threshold density of $\text{AC}^{0}$, which are related to information theory and computational geometry, making cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) possible sub-categories as well.
